Test with this:

  # ASCII
  $ lpdoc -d filepath=`pwd` -d allow_markdown=yes -d doc_mainopts=no_versioned_output -c markdown_simple.ascii
  $ lpdoc -d filepath=`pwd` -d allow_markdown=no -d doc_mainopts=no_versioned_output -c markup_simple.ascii

  # HTML
  $ lpdoc -v -d filepath=`pwd` -d allow_markdown=yes -d doc_mainopts=no_versioned_output -c markdown_simple.html/markdown_simple.htmlmeta
  $ lpdoc -v -d filepath=`pwd` -d allow_markdown=no -d doc_mainopts=no_versioned_output -c markup_simple.html/markup_simple.htmlmeta

  # PDF
  $ lpdoc -v -d filepath=`pwd` -d allow_markdown=yes -d doc_mainopts=no_versioned_output -c markdown_simple.pdf
  $ lpdoc -v -d filepath=`pwd` -d allow_markdown=no -d doc_mainopts=no_versioned_output -c markup_simple.pdf

Add "-d syntax_highlight=yes" to generate HTML output with syntax
highlight.

The output of both markup and markdown versions should be similar (not
equivalent at this moment since the markdown versions contains notes).

